In 2019, attention was drawn to cancer in Kenya following the death of high profile politicians, giving hope to many patients that their outcome would change. In 2020, however, new data showed the country recorded 42,116 new cases with the number of deaths rising to 27,092.
A delay in cancer diagnosis can occur at various levels. For example, the patient may fail to recognise suspicious symptoms or act on them, or the primary care physician may fail to pick up on these suspicious symptoms and investigate them appropriately or refer the patients to other specialists in a timely fashion.





Professor George Njoroge, the Chief Scientific Adviser at the Kenyatta University Teaching Referral and Research Hospital (KUTRRH), during an interview at his office on January 20, 2021. 
Photo credit: Dennis Onsongo | Nation Media Group


More specialists



